<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="423" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1127,653,1189]" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,295,653,677]" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lucas" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[300,550,654,677]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Aulacophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foveicollis">
<emphasis box="[300,550,654,677]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">Aulacophora foveicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in southern Palearctic, African and Oriental Regions. It was reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[570,644,685,708]" name="Yemen" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">Yemen</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="BRYANT G. E." box="[685,845,685,709]" pageId="20" pageNumber="423" pagination="353 - 363" refId="ref13577" refString="BRYANT G. E. 1957: Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae of South-West Arabia. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 12 10: 353 - 363." type="journal article" year="1957">BRYANT (1957)</bibRefCitation>
. However, re-examination of those specimens is necessary to decide if his specimens belong to the true 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lucas" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[980,1120,718,741]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Aulacophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foveicollis">
<emphasis box="[980,1120,718,741]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">A. foveicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Anand &amp; Cox" authorityYear="1986" box="[151,239,750,773]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Aulacophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="calva">
<emphasis box="[151,239,750,773]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">A. calva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or unclear species of 
<taxonomicName box="[472,611,750,773]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Aulacophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[472,611,750,773]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">Aulacophora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see below).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="423" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1127,653,1189]" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,283,781,805]" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">Comments.</emphasis>
All three recently collected specimens have yellow underside, only abdomen has black lateral margins. The median lobe of the male last visible ventrite is shallowly impressed but its apex has a deep transverse oval cavity (
<figureCitation box="[763,844,845,869]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="21.[111,150,1520,1539]" captionTargetBox="[173,1030,229,1489]" captionTargetId="figure-13@21.[165,1036,219,1496]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figs. 39–42. 32–34. Aulacophora cf. foveicollis (Lucas, 1847). 39 – habitus of male (7.1 mm); 40 – male abdomen; 41 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view, b – lateral view). 42 – aedeagus of Aulacophora foveicollis sensu BERTI (1990) (a – dorsal view, b – lateral view). Scale bar 1 mm for Fig. 41." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339736" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339736/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
). The body lenght of three available males: 7.0– 
<quantity box="[382,468,877,901]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.2" pageId="20" pageNumber="423" unit="mm" value="7.2">7.2 mm</quantity>
. The same colouration of underside was reported by MEDVEDEV (1996) for specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lucas" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[473,616,910,933]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Aulacophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foveicollis">
<emphasis box="[473,616,910,933]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">A. foveicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[686,833,909,933]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
. Although the aedeagus of the Yemeni specimens is very similar to that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lucas" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[665,807,942,965]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Aulacophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foveicollis">
<emphasis box="[665,807,942,965]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">A. foveicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as published by 
<bibRefCitation author="BERTI N." box="[988,1126,941,965]" pageId="20" pageNumber="423" pagination="109 - 126" refId="ref13361" refString="BERTI N. 1990: Contribution a l' etude des Galerucinae afrotropicaux. IX. - Le genre Aulacophora Chevrolat, description d' un genre nouveau, Chosnia gen. nov. (Coleoptera, Chrysomelidae). Journal of African Zoology 104: 109 - 126." type="journal article" year="1990">BERTI (1990)</bibRefCitation>
(see 
<figureCitation box="[204,339,973,997]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="21.[111,150,1520,1539]" captionTargetBox="[173,1030,229,1489]" captionTargetId="figure-13@21.[165,1036,219,1496]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figs. 39–42. 32–34. Aulacophora cf. foveicollis (Lucas, 1847). 39 – habitus of male (7.1 mm); 40 – male abdomen; 41 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view, b – lateral view). 42 – aedeagus of Aulacophora foveicollis sensu BERTI (1990) (a – dorsal view, b – lateral view). Scale bar 1 mm for Fig. 41." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5339736" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5339736/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">Figs. 41, 42</figureCitation>
), I have some doubts that my and Medvedev′ s specimens belong to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lucas" baseAuthorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Aulacophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foveicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">A. foveicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because this species has abdomen black with orange median lobe of the last male ventrite only. In my opinion specimens from the Arabian Peninsula may represent an undescribed species but I am unable to make a comprehensive revision of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lucas" baseAuthorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Aulacophora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="423" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foveicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="423">Aulacophora foveicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
material necessary for such decision at the moment. Moreover, I have not seen any female from the Arabian population whose structure of abdomen and pygidium can also help to unravel this problem.
</paragraph>
